<subSubSection id="192864AF10137104DBCCF83136AAF91D" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="DBD17F3B6DD00B2228A5B81C6A7811D9" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9FD6018259CE8FB2FA636BC99F1BA60F" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="BE728F32CA79973E7D1D064306922C8F" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" refId="B4" refString="Michener, CD, 2007. The Bees of the World (2nd edn). The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore" title="The Bees of the World (2 nd edn)." year="2007">Michener (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="BBDC5408DAD257F2F6F8AE0D7C358627" DOI="http://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3218.1.6" author="Niu, ZQ" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" pagination="59 - 68" refId="B5" refString="Niu, ZQ, Wu, YR, Zhu, CD, 2012. A new species of Bathanthidium Mavromoustakis (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae: Anthidiini) from China, with a key to the species. Zootaxa 3218: 59 - 68, DOI: http://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3218.1.6" title="A new species of Bathanthidium Mavromoustakis (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae: Anthidiini) from China, with a key to the species." url="http://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3218.1.6" volume="3218" year="2012">Niu et al. (2012)</bibRefCitation>
, the diagnosis of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="EC584E18E7ED9EE3FCCF159609A8314F" authorityName="Mavromoustakis" authorityYear="1953" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Bathanthidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bathanthidium" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C2502B71C67360AB965CB40432F43511" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Bathanthidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is as follows: Small to moderate-sized species. Body all black or black with yellow markings, with the yellow bands broken on anterior terga; epistomal suture generally straight; medially divided, smooth-floored mesoscuto-mesoscutoscutellar sulcus; preoccipital ridge not carinate; omaular carina absent; pronotal lobe with carina weak or absent; scutellum rounded or medially emarginated, in profile rounded or at least not sharp and not overhanging metanotum; propodeum with a fovea behind spiracle; 2nd m-cu slightly exceeding the apical margin of 2nd submarginal cell; arolia present and large; median S4 of both sexes with pectinate hairs; S5 of the male with pectinate hairs; T6 of the male simple; T7 of the male ranges from simple to trilobed, with the median lobe longest; front coxa of the male normal, without spine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
